# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: appendicitis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Abdominal angina is caused by obstruction or stenosis of the inferior mesenteric artery, celiac trunk, or superior mesenteric artery.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Gender, age, smoking, hypertension, diabetes, and hyperlipidemia are risk factors for abdominal angina.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] The digestive tract relies on the celiac, superior mesenteric, and inferior mesenteric arteries for blood flow.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Abdominal pain occurs when these arteries fail to provide adequate blood flow.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Abdominal angina is diagnosed using imaging to identify stenosis.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Differential diagnoses include GERD, dietary sensitivities, constipation, pancreatitis, abdominal abscess, appendicitis, irritable bowel syndrome, gastroenteritis, hepatitis, and gastrointestinal system inflammation.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Chronic mesenteric ischemia requires surgical revascularization and treatment like stents, transaortic endarterectomy, or bypassing the arteries.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Abdominal angina often has a one-year delay between symptoms and treatment, leading to complications like malnutrition or bowel infarction.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Abdominal angina is more prevalent in females with a 3:1 ratio, and the average age of onset is 60 years.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Abdominal angina was first described by Dr.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Baccelli in 1918 as lower abdominal pain after eating.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Symptoms of abdominal angina include postprandial abdominal pain, weight loss, diarrhea, nausea, vomiting, and an aversion or fear of eating caused by the pain associated with eating.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Abdominal angina usually starts 30 minutes after eating and persists for one to three hours.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Individuals typically express the pain as a dull ache by clenching their fists over the epigastrium (Levine sign).
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Sometimes people may reduce their caloric intake in an attempt to decrease pain which can lead to weight loss.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] There may also be changes in bowel habits, most commonly diarrhea from malabsorption or rarely constipation.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Abdominal angina is caused by obstruction or stenosis of the inferior mesenteric artery (IMA), celiac trunk, or superior mesenteric artery (SMA).
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] More than 95% of abdominal angina is caused by stenosis of the splanchnic arteries due to local atherosclerosis.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] The occlusion mainly affects the ostia or the last few centimetres of the mesenteric arteries.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] In rare cases, compression of the celiac trunk by the diaphragm's arcuate ligament can result in isolated occlusive disease (also known as "median arcuate ligament syndrome").
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Other less common causes of vascular obstruction include vasculitis, chronic mesenteric venous thrombosis, fibromuscular dysplasia, radiation enteritis, and, in rare cases, extrinsic obstruction or vessel encasement by a tumour.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Approximately 82% of those with abdominal angina have diabetes.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Hyperlipidemia, which frequently causes peripheral vascular disease, raises the risk of abdominal angina by 70% and correlates with the atherosclerotic aspect of the disease process.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Smoking plays a part in the development of abdominal angina.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Smokers account for 75% to 80% of all abdominal angina cases.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] The average age of onset is more than 60.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] This data corresponds with the vascular damage that occurs with age.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Gender appears to play a role in the development of abdominal angina.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Women are threefold more likely to develop abdominal angina than men.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Hypertension is another known risk factor.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Six out of ten of those with abdominal angina will be hypertensive.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Blood supply of the gastrointestinal system.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] The celiac, superior mesenteric, and inferior mesenteric arteries are the three primary blood vessels that support the digestive tract.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Abdominal pain happens because the digestive processes require increased blood flow to the stomach.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] The stenotic or occluded artery cannot give adequate blood flow.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] The pain is caused by ischemia of the affected tissues, which do not receive the essential perfusion to perform digestion.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] The gastrointestinal system has significant collateral circulation, which may worsen in cases of vascular stenosis.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Along with the protection provided by collateral blood flow, the colon possesses various other mechanisms to prevent ischemia, such as opening of all mesenteric capillaries, redistribution of intramural blood supply, and improved oxygen extraction.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] But if those are exceeded, these defensive mechanisms become overwhelmed and no longer provide protection.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Some people with a single-vessel lesion experience symptoms, while others with up to three lesions are asymptomatic; hence, the number of arteries required to cause symptoms of ischemia is debatable.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] The occurrence of angina is determined by factors besides the number of arteries affected, such as the location of the lesion, the time of advancement of the lesions, and concurrent disorders that impact angiogenesis.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Abdominal angina is diagnosed by identifying stenosis with imaging.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Since the symptoms of abdominal angina overlap with various other disorders, other causes of symptoms are ruled out as a part of the diagnostic process.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Gastric ulcers, abdominal aortic aneurysms, and gastrointestinal cancers can have similar symptoms and can be ruled out by esophagogastroduodenoscopy, CT scans, or MR angiogram.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Other differential diagnoses include GERD, dietary or food sensitivities, constipation, pancreatitis, abdominal abscess, appendicitis, irritable bowel syndrome, gastroenteritis, hepatitis, and inflammation of the gastrointestinal system.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Duplex ultrasound, MR angiography, angiography, and computed tomography angiography can be used to help confirm the diagnosis of abdominal angina.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Duplex ultrasound may be used to screen for abdominal angina but is not ideal for visualizing stenosis.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Angiography, MR angiography, or CT angiography can be used to further visualize the celiac and mesenteric arteries.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Abdominal angina is treated differently based on the severity and cause.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Antibiotics are often used in the case of colonic ischemia as there is often cooccurring infections.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] When possible the underlying cause of abdominal angina may be treated.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] This includes medications to treat heart failure, hypertension, dysrhythmia, or hyperlipidemia.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] The most effective treatment for chronic mesenteric ischemia is surgical revascularization and percutaneous treatment such as stents.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Surgical treatment may include transaortic endarterectomy of the effected arteries or creating a retrograde or anterograde bypass in the arteries.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Similarly to other vascular disorders, abdominal angina can be slowly progressive.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] There is often a one-year delay between the onset of symptoms and treatment.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Complications of abdominal angina such as malnutrition or bowel infarction can cause increased morbidity and mortality in this population.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] The prevalence of abdominal angina is unknown.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] It is more prevalent in females than males with a ratio of 3:1.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] The mean age of those affected is 60 years old.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] The term "abdominal angina" was first used by Dr.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] He used the term to describe a group of patients who had developed lower abdominal pain after eating.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] In 1936 Dunphy made the connection between abdominal angina and gastrointestinal necrosis.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] 21 years later Mikkelson introduced a surgery which could help restore blood flow to the gastrointestinal system.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-angina] Although there was early interest in research, there has been very little subsequent research in the years following.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] AAAs occur most commonly in men, those over 50, and those with a family history of the disease.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Additional risk factors include smoking, high blood pressure, and other heart or blood vessel diseases.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Genetic conditions with an increased risk include Marfan syndrome and Ehlers–Danlos syndrome.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] AAAs are the most common form of aortic aneurysm.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] About 85% occur below the kidneys, with the rest either at the level of or above the kidneys.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] In the United States, screening with abdominal ultrasound is recommended for males between 65 and 75 years of age with a history of smoking.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] In the United Kingdom and Sweden, screening all men over 65 is recommended.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Abstinence from cigarette smoking is the single best way to prevent the disease.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Other methods of prevention include treating high blood pressure, treating high blood cholesterol, and avoiding being overweight.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Surgery is usually recommended when the diameter of an AAA grows to >5.5 cm in males and >5.0 cm in females.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Other reasons for repair include symptoms and a rapid increase in size, defined as more than one centimeter per year.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Repair may be either by open surgery or endovascular aneurysm repair (EVAR).
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] As compared to open surgery, EVAR has a lower risk of death in the short term and a shorter hospital stay, but may not always be an option.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] There does not appear to be a difference in longer-term outcomes between the two.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Repeat procedures are more common with EVAR.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] AAAs affect 2–8% of males over the age of 65.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] In those with an aneurysm less than 5.5 cm, the risk of rupture in the next year is below 1%.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Among those with an aneurysm between 5.5 and 7 cm, the risk is about 10%, while for those with an aneurysm greater than 7 cm the risk is about 33%.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] In the United States AAAs resulted in between 10,000 and 18,000 deaths in 2009.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The vast majority of aneurysms are asymptomatic.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] However, as the abdominal aorta expands and/or ruptures, the aneurysm may become painful and lead to pulsating sensations in the abdomen or pain in the chest, lower back, legs, or scrotum.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The complications include rupture, peripheral embolization, acute aortic occlusion, and aortocaval (between the aorta and inferior vena cava) or aortoduodenal (between the aorta and the duodenum) fistulae.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] On physical examination, a palpable and pulsatile abdominal mass can be noted.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Bruits can be present in case of renal or visceral arterial stenosis.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The signs and symptoms of a ruptured AAA may include severe pain in the lower back, flank, abdomen, or groin.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] A mass that pulses with the heartbeat may also be felt.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The bleeding can lead to a hypovolemic shock with low blood pressure and a fast heart rate, which may cause fainting.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The mortality of AAA rupture is as high as 90 percent.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] 65 to 75 percent of patients die before they arrive at the hospital and up to 90 percent die before they reach the operating room.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The bleeding can be retroperitoneal or into the abdominal cavity.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Rupture can also create a connection between the aorta and intestine or inferior vena cava.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Flank ecchymosis (appearance of a bruise) is a sign of retroperitoneal bleeding and is also called Grey Turner's sign.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The exact causes of the degenerative process remain unclear.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] There are, however, some hypotheses and well-defined risk factors.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The most striking histopathological changes of the aneurysmatic aorta are seen in the tunica media and intima layers.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] These changes include the accumulation of lipids in foam cells, extracellular free cholesterol crystals, calcifications, thrombosis, and ulcerations and ruptures of the layers.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Adventitial inflammatory infiltrate is present.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] However, the degradation of the tunica media by means of a proteolytic process seems to be the basic pathophysiologic mechanism of AAA development.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Some researchers report increased expression and activity of matrix metalloproteinases in individuals with AAA.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] This leads to the elimination of elastin from the media, rendering the aortic wall more susceptible to the influence of blood pressure.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Other reports have suggested the serine protease granzyme B may contribute to aortic aneurysm rupture through the cleavage of decorin, leading to disrupted collagen organization and reduced tensile strength of the adventitia.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] There is also a reduced amount of vasa vasorum in the abdominal aorta (compared to the thoracic aorta); consequently, the tunica media must rely mostly on diffusion for nutrition, which makes it more susceptible to damage.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Hemodynamics affect the development of AAA, which has a predilection for the infrarenal aorta.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The histological structure and mechanical characteristics of the infrarenal aorta differ from those of the thoracic aorta.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The diameter decreases from the root to the aortic bifurcation, and the wall of the infrarenal aorta also contains a lesser proportion of elastin.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The mechanical tension in the abdominal aortic wall is therefore higher than in the thoracic aortic wall.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The elasticity and distensibility also decline with age, which can result in gradual dilatation of the segment.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Higher intraluminal pressure in patients with arterial hypertension markedly contributes to the progression of the pathological process.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Suitable hemodynamic conditions may be linked to specific intraluminal thrombus (ILT) patterns along the aortic lumen, which in turn may affect AAA's development.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] An abdominal aortic aneurysm is usually diagnosed by physical exam, abdominal ultrasound, or CT scan.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Plain abdominal radiographs may show the outline of an aneurysm when its walls are calcified.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] However, the outline will be visible by X-ray in less than half of all aneurysms.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Ultrasonography is used to screen for aneurysms and to determine their size if present.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Additionally, free peritoneal fluid can be detected.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] It is non-invasive and sensitive, but the presence of bowel gas or obesity may limit its usefulness.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] CT scan has nearly 100% sensitivity for an aneurysm and is also useful in preoperative planning, detailing the anatomy and possibility for endovascular repair.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] In the case of suspected rupture, it can also reliably detect retroperitoneal fluid.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Alternative less often used methods for visualization of an aneurysm include MRI and angiography.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] An aneurysm ruptures if the mechanical stress (tension per area) exceeds the local wall strength; consequently, peak wall stress (PWS), mean wall stress (MWS), and peak wall rupture risk (PWRR) are more reliable parameters than diameter to assess AAA rupture risk.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Medical software allows computing these rupture risk indices from standard clinical CT data and provides a patient-specific AAA rupture risk diagnosis.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] This type of biomechanical approach has been shown to accurately predict the location of AAA rupture.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Abdominal aortic aneurysms are commonly divided according to their size and symptomatology.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] An aneurysm is usually defined as an outer aortic diameter over 3 cm (normal diameter of the aorta is around 2 cm), or more than 50% of normal diameter.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] If the outer diameter exceeds 5.5 cm, the aneurysm is considered to be large.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Ruptured AAA should be suspected in any person older than 60 who experiences collapse, unexplained low blood pressure, or sudden-onset back or abdominal pain.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Abdominal pain, shock, and a pulsatile mass are only present in a minority of cases.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Although an unstable person with a known aneurysm may undergo surgery without further imaging, the diagnosis will usually be confirmed using CT or ultrasound scanning.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The suprarenal aorta normally measures about 0.5 cm larger than the infrarenal aorta.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Aortic aneurysm rupture may be mistaken for the pain of kidney stones, or muscle related back pain.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Preventive Services Task Force (USPSTF) recommends a single screening abdominal ultrasound for abdominal aortic aneurysm in males aged 65 to 75 years who have a history of smoking.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Among this group who does not smoke, screening may be selective.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] It is unclear if screening is useful in women who have smoked and the USPSTF recommends against screening in women who have never smoked.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] In the United Kingdom, the NHS AAA Screening Programme invites men in England for screening during the year they turn 65.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Men over 65 can contact the programme to arrange to be screened.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] In Sweden one time screening is recommended in all males over 65 years of age.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] This has been found to decrease the risk of death from AAA by 42% with a number needed to screen just over 200.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] In those with a close relative diagnosed with an aortic aneurysm, Swedish guidelines recommend an ultrasound at around 60 years of age.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Australia has no guideline on screening.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Repeat ultrasounds should be carried out in those who have an aortic size greater than 3.0 cm.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Although recommendations vary between guidelines, in those whose aorta is between 3.0 and 3.9 cm this may be every three years, if between 4.0 and 4.4 cm every two years, and if between 4.5 and 5.4 cm every year.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The treatment options for asymptomatic AAA are conservative management, surveillance with a view to eventual repair, and immediate repair.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Two modes of repair are available for an AAA: open aneurysm repair, and endovascular aneurysm repair (EVAR).
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] An intervention is often recommended if the aneurysm grows more than 1 cm per year or it is bigger than 5.5 cm.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Repair is also indicated for symptomatic aneurysms.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Ten years after open AAA repair, the overall survival rate was 59%.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Mycotic abdominal aorta aneurysm (MAAA) is a rare and life-threatening condition.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Because of its rarity, there is a lack of adequately powered studies and consensus on its treatment and follow-up.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] A management protocol on the management of mycotic abdominal aortic aneurysm was recently published in the Annals of Vascular Surgery by Premnath et al.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Conservative management is indicated in people where repair carries a high mortality risk and in patients where repair is unlikely to improve life expectancy.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The mainstay of the conservative treatment is smoking cessation.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Surveillance is indicated in small asymptomatic aneurysms (less than 5.5 cm) where the risk of repair exceeds the risk of rupture.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] As an AAA grows in diameter, the risk of rupture increases.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Surveillance until an aneurysm has reached a diameter of 5.5 cm has not been shown to have a higher risk as compared to early intervention.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] No medical therapy has been proven to be effective at decreasing the growth rate or rupture rate of asymptomatic AAAs, though observational data suggest statins may attenuate both growth rate and risk of surgery.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Blood pressure and lipids should, however, be treated per usual.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The use of statins in moderate or high intensity in patients with atherosclerotic AAAs reduces the risk of adverse events such as myocardial infarction and stroke.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The threshold for repair varies slightly from individual to individual, depending on the balance of risks and benefits when considering repair versus ongoing surveillance.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The size of an individual's native aorta may influence this, along with the presence of comorbidities that increase operative risk or decrease life expectancy.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Evidence, however, favors elective repair if the AAA size is greater than 5.5 cm in men and 5.0 cm in women.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Surgery is usually recommended for symptomatic patients.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Limited evidence suggests intervention in case of saccular aneurysms, as their shape may result in earlier rupture, as well as rapidly-growing AAAs (≥0.5 cm in 6 months or ≥1 cm in one year).
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Open repair is indicated in young patients as an elective procedure, or in growing or large, symptomatic or ruptured aneurysms.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The aorta must be clamped during the repair, denying blood to the abdominal organs and sections of the spinal cord; this can cause a range of complications.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] As it is essential to perform the critical part of the operation quickly, the incision is typically made large enough to facilitate the fastest repair.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Recovery after open AAA surgery takes significant time.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The minimums are a few days in intensive care, a week total in the hospital, and a few months before full recovery.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Endovascular repair first became practical in the 1990s and although it is now an established alternative to open repair, its role is yet to be clearly defined.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] It is generally indicated in older, high-risk patients or patients unfit for open repair.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] However, endovascular repair is feasible for only a portion of AAAs, depending on the morphology of the aneurysm.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The main advantages over open repair are that there is less peri-operative mortality, less time in intensive care, less time in hospital overall, and an earlier return to normal activity.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Disadvantages of endovascular repair include a requirement for more frequent ongoing hospital reviews and a higher chance of further required procedures.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] According to the latest studies, the EVAR procedure does not offer any benefit for overall survival or health-related quality of life compared to open surgery, although aneurysm-related mortality is lower.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] In patients unfit for open repair, EVAR plus conservative management was associated with no benefit, more complications, subsequent procedures and higher costs compared to conservative management alone.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Endovascular treatment for paraanastomotic aneurysms after aortobiiliac reconstruction is also a possibility.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] A 2017 Cochrane review found tentative evidence of no difference in outcomes between endovascular and open repair of ruptured AAA in the first month.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] In those with aortic rupture of the AAA, treatment is immediate surgical repair.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] There appear to be benefits to allowing permissive hypotension and limiting the use of intravenous fluids during transport to the operating room.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Although the current standard of determining rupture risk is based on maximum diameter, it is known that smaller AAAs that fall below this threshold (diameter<5.5 cm) may also rupture, and larger AAAs (diameter>5.5 cm) may remain stable.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] In one report, it was shown that 10–24% of ruptured AAAs were less than 5 cm in diameter.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] It has also been reported that of 473 non-repaired AAAs examined from autopsy reports, there were 118 cases of rupture, 13% of which were less than 5 cm in diameter.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] This study also showed that 60% of the AAAs greater than 5 cm (including 54% of those AAAs between 7.1 and 10 cm) never experienced rupture.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Alternative methods of rupture assessment have been recently reported.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The majority of these approaches involve the numerical analysis of AAAs using the common engineering technique of the finite element method (FEM) to determine the wall stress distributions.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Recent reports have shown that these stress distributions have been shown to correlate to the overall geometry of the AAA rather than solely to the maximum diameter.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] It is also known that wall stress alone does not completely govern failure as an AAA will usually rupture when the wall stress exceeds the wall strength.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] In light of this, rupture assessment may be more accurate if the patient-specific wall stress is coupled together with patient-specific wall strength.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] A noninvasive method of determining patient-dependent wall strength was recently reported, with more traditional approaches to strength determination via tensile testing performed by other researchers in the field.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Machine learning models are being investigated to improve predictions of rupture risk and the need for surgical repair, with the aim of enabling more individualised management recommendations.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Such tools could be particularly impactful in countries with established screening programmes.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The postoperative mortality for an already ruptured AAA has slowly decreased over several decades but remains higher than 40%.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] However, if the AAA is surgically repaired before rupture, the postoperative mortality rate is substantially lower, approximately 1-6%.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The occurrence of AAA varies by ethnicity.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] In the United Kingdom, the rate of AAA in Caucasian men older than 65 years is about 4.7%, while in Asian men it is 0.45%.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] It is also less common in individuals of African, and Hispanic heritage.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] They occur four times more often in men than in women.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] There are at least 13,000 deaths yearly in the U.S. secondary to AAA rupture.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The peak number of new cases per year among males is around 70 years of age, and the percentage of males affected over 60 years is 2–6%.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The frequency is much higher in smokers than in non-smokers (8:1), and the risk decreases slowly after smoking cessation.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] In the U.S., the incidence of AAA is 2–4% in the adult population.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Rupture of the AAA occurs in 1–3% of men aged 65 or more, for whom the mortality rate is 70–95%.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The first historical records about AAA are from Ancient Rome in the 2nd century AD, when Greek surgeon Antyllus tried to treat the AAA with proximal and distal ligature, central incision and removal of thrombotic material from the aneurysm.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] However, attempts to treat the AAA surgically were unsuccessful until 1923.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] In that year, Rudolph Matas (who also proposed the concept of endoaneurysmorrhaphy), performed the first successful aortic ligation on a human.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Other methods that were successful in treating the AAA included wrapping the aorta with polyethene cellophane, which induced fibrosis and restricted the growth of the aneurysm.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Endovascular aneurysm repair was first performed in the late 1980s and has been widely adopted in the subsequent decades.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Endovascular repair was first used for treating a ruptured aneurysm in Nottingham in 1994.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Theoretical physicist Albert Einstein underwent an operation for an abdominal aortic aneurysm in 1949 that was performed by Rudolph Nissen, who wrapped the aorta with polyethylene cellophane.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Einstein's aneurysm ruptured on April 13, 1955.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] He declined surgery, saying, "I want to go when I want.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] It is tasteless to prolong life artificially.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] I will do it elegantly." He died five days later at age 76.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] French general and statesman Charles de Gaulle died suddenly from an abdominal aortic aneurysm while watching the news on television on the evening of November 9th, 1970, less than 2 weeks before his 80th birthday.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Actor John Banner, January 28, 1910 – January 28, 1973, famous for portraying Sgt.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Shultz on Hogan's Heroes, died from an abdominal aortic aneurysm on his 63rd birthday while visiting friends in Vienna.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Actress Lucille Ball died on April 26, 1989, from an abdominal aortic aneurysm.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] At the time of her death, she was in Cedars-Sinai Medical Center recovering from emergency surgery performed just six days earlier because of a dissecting aortic aneurysm near her heart.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Ball was at increased risk as she had been a heavy smoker for decades.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Musician Conway Twitty died in June 1993 from an abdominal aortic aneurysm at the age of 59, two months before the release of what would be his final studio album, *Final Touches*.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Scott died in 1999, aged 71, from a ruptured abdominal aortic aneurysm.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] In 2001, former presidential candidate Bob Dole underwent surgery for an abdominal aortic aneurysm in which a team led by vascular surgeon Kenneth Ouriel inserted a stent graft.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Actor Robert Jacks, who played Leatherface in *Texas Chainsaw Massacre: The Next Generation*, died from an abdominal aneurysm on August 8, 2001, one day shy of his 42nd birthday.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] When Jacks was a child, his father died from the same cause.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Actor Tommy Ford died of abdominal aneurysm in October 2016 at 52 years old.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Gary Gygax, co-creator of *Dungeons & Dragons*, died from an abdominal aortic aneurysm in 2008, at the age of 69.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Harvey Korman died on May 29, 2008, aged 81, as the result of complications from a ruptured abdominal aortic aneurysm he had suffered four months earlier.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] There have been many calls for alternative approaches to rupture risk assessment over the past number of years, with many believing that a biomechanics-based approach may be more suitable than the current diameter approach.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Numerical modeling is a valuable tool to researchers allowing approximate wall stresses to be calculated, thus revealing the rupture potential of a particular aneurysm.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Experimental models are required to validate these numerical results and provide further insight into the biomechanical behavior of the AAA.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] *In vivo*, AAAs exhibit a varying range of material strengths from localised weak hypoxic regions to much stronger regions and areas of calcifications.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Finding ways to predict future AAA growth is seen as a research priority.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Another related line of research is utilizing mathematical decision modeling (e.g., Markov decision processes) to determine improved treatment policies.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Initial results suggest that a more dynamic policy could provide benefits, although such claims have not been clinically verified.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] A study recently showed that aneurysms can be accurately predicted as to whether they are stable (lacking repair or intervention), requiring repair, or at risk of rupture from scans years prior to any event based on a machine-learning based classification tool.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Experimental models can now be manufactured using a novel technique involving the injection-moulding lost-wax manufacturing process to create patient-specific anatomically correct AAA replicas.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Work has also focused on developing more realistic material analogues to those *in vivo*, and recently a novel range of silicone-rubbers was created allowing the varying material properties of the AAA to be more accurately represented.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] These rubber models can also be used in a variety of experimental situations, from stress analysis using the photoelastic method New endovascular devices are being developed that are able to treat more complex and tortuous anatomies.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] An animal study showed that removing a single protein prevents early damage in blood vessels from triggering a later-stage, frequently lethal complication.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] By eliminating the gene for a signaling protein called cyclophilin A (CypA) from a strain of mice, researchers were able to provide complete protection against abdominal aortic aneurysm.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Other recent research identified Granzyme B (GZMB) (a protein-degrading enzyme) to be a potential target in the treatment of abdominal aortic aneurysms.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Elimination of this enzyme in mice models both slowed the progression of aneurysms and improved survival.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The mechanisms that lead to AAA development are still not completely understood at a cellular and molecular level.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] To better understand the pathophysiology of AAA, it is often necessary to use experimental animal models.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] It is often questioned how well these models translate to human disease.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Even though no animal model exactly represents the human condition, all the existing ones focus on one different pathophysiological aspect of the disease.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] Combining the results from different animal models with clinical research can provide a better overview of the AAA pathophysiology.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The most common animal models are rodents (mice and rats), although, for certain studies, such as testing preclinical devices or surgical procedures, large animal models (pig, sheep) are more frequently used.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The rodent models of AAA can be classified according to different aspects.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] There are dissecting models vs non-dissecting models and genetically determined models vs chemically induced models.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] The most commonly used models are the angiotensin-II infusion into ApoE knockout mice (dissecting model, chemically induced), the calcium chloride model (non-dissecting, chemically induced), and the elastase model (non-dissecting, chemically induced model).
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-aortic-aneurysm] A recent study has shown that β-Aminopropionitrile plus elastase application to abdominal aorta causes more severe aneurysm in mice as compared to elastase alone.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] The **abdominal cavity** is a large body cavity in humans and many other animals that contains organs.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] It is a part of the abdominopelvic cavity.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] It is located below the thoracic cavity, and above the pelvic cavity.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] Its dome-shaped roof is the thoracic diaphragm, a thin sheet of muscle under the lungs, and its floor is the pelvic inlet, opening into the pelvis.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] Organs of the abdominal cavity include the stomach, liver, gallbladder, spleen, pancreas, small intestine, kidneys, large intestine, and adrenal glands.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] The abdominal cavity is lined with a protective membrane termed the peritoneum.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] The inside wall is covered by the parietal peritoneum.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] The kidneys are located behind the peritoneum, in the retroperitoneum, outside the abdominal cavity.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] The viscera are also covered by visceral peritoneum.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] Between the visceral and parietal peritoneum is the peritoneal cavity, which is a potential space.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] It contains a serous fluid called peritoneal fluid that allows motion.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] This motion is apparent of the gastrointestinal tract.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] The peritoneum, by virtue of its connection to the two (parietal and visceral) portions, gives support to the abdominal organs.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] The peritoneum divides the cavity into numerous compartments.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] One of these the lesser sac is located behind the stomach and joins into the greater sac via the foramen of Winslow.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] Some of the organs are attached to the walls of the abdomen via folds of peritoneum and ligaments, such as the liver and others use broad areas of the peritoneum, such as the pancreas.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] The peritoneal ligaments are actually dense folds of the peritoneum that are used to connect viscera to viscera or viscera to the walls of the abdomen.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] They are named in such a way as to show what they connect typically.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] For example, the gastrocolic ligament connects the stomach and colon and the splenocolic ligament connects the spleen and the colon, or sometimes by their shape as the round ligament or triangular ligament.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] Mesenteries are folds of peritoneum that are attached to the walls of the abdomen and enclose viscera completely.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] They are supplied with plentiful amounts of blood.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] The three most important mesenteries are mesentery for the small intestine, the transverse mesocolon, which attaches the back portion of the colon to the abdominal wall, and the sigmoid mesocolon which enfolds the sigmoid colon.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] The omentum are specialized folds of peritoneum that enclose nerves, blood vessels, lymph channels, fatty tissue, and connective tissue.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] First, is the greater omentum that hangs off of the transverse colon and greater curvature of the stomach.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] The other is the lesser omentum that extends between the stomach and the liver.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] When fluid collects in the abdominal cavity, this condition is called ascites.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] This is usually not noticeable until enough fluid has collected to distend the abdomen.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] The collection of fluid will cause pressure on the viscera, veins, and thoracic cavity.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] Treatment is directed at the cause of the fluid accumulation.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] One method is to decrease the portal vein pressure, especially useful in treating cirrhosis.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] Chylous ascites heals best if the lymphatic vessel involved is closed.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] Heart failure can cause recurring ascites.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] Another disorder is called peritonitis which usually accompanies inflammatory processes elsewhere.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] It can be caused by damage to an organ, or from a contusion to the abdominal wall from the outside or by surgery.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] It may be brought in by the bloodstream or the lymphatic system.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] The most common origin is the gastrointestinal tract.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] Peritonitis can be acute or chronic, generalized or localized, and may have one origin or multiple origins.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] The omenta can help control the spread of infection; however without treatment, the infection will spread throughout the cavity.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] An abscess may also form as a secondary reaction to an infection.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-cavity] Antibiotics have become an important tool in fighting abscesses; however, external drainage is usually required also.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-guarding] Guarding is a characteristic finding in the physical examination for an abruptly painful abdomen (an acute abdomen) with inflammation of the inner abdominal (peritoneal) surface due, for example, to appendicitis or diverticulitis.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-guarding] The tensed muscles of the abdominal wall automatically go into spasm to keep the tender underlying tissues from being disturbed.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Common causes of pain in the abdomen include gastroenteritis and irritable bowel syndrome.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] About 15% of people have a more serious underlying condition such as appendicitis, leaking or ruptured abdominal aortic aneurysm, diverticulitis, or ectopic pregnancy.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] In a third of cases, the exact cause is unclear.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] The onset of abdominal pain can be abrupt, quick, or gradual.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Sudden onset pain happens nearly instantaneously.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Rapidly onset pain starts mild and gets worse over the next few minutes.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Pain that gradually intensifies only after several hours or even days has passed is referred to as gradual onset pain.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] One can describe abdominal pain as either continuous or sporadic and as cramping, dull, or aching.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] The characteristic of cramping abdominal pain is that it comes in brief waves, builds to a peak, and then abruptly stops for a period during which there is no more pain.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] The pain flares up and off periodically.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] The most common cause of persistent dull or aching abdominal pain is edema or distention of the wall of a hollow viscus.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] A dull or aching pain may also be felt due to a stretch in the liver and spleen capsules.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] The most frequent reasons for abdominal pain are gastroenteritis (13%), irritable bowel syndrome (8%), urinary tract problems (5%), inflammation of the stomach (5%) and constipation (5%).
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] In about 30% of cases, the cause is not determined.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] About 10% of cases have a more serious cause including gallbladder (gallstones or biliary dyskinesia) or pancreas problems (4%), diverticulitis (3%), appendicitis (2%) and cancer (1%).
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] More common in those who are older, ischemic colitis, mesenteric ischemia, and abdominal aortic aneurysms are other serious causes.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Acute abdomen is a condition where there is a sudden onset of severe abdominal pain requiring immediate recognition and management of the underlying cause.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] The underlying cause may involve infection, inflammation, vascular occlusion or bowel obstruction.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] The pain may elicit nausea and vomiting, abdominal distention, fever and signs of shock.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] A common condition associated with acute abdominal pain is appendicitis.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] The location of abdominal pain can provide information about what may be causing the pain.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] The abdomen can be divided into four regions called quadrants.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Abdominal pain can be referred to as visceral pain or peritoneal pain.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] The contents of the abdomen can be divided into the foregut, midgut, and hindgut.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] The foregut contains the pharynx, lower respiratory tract, portions of the esophagus, stomach, portions of the duodenum (proximal), liver, biliary tract (including the gallbladder and bile ducts), and the pancreas.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] The midgut contains portions of the duodenum (distal), cecum, appendix, ascending colon, and first half of the transverse colon.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] The hindgut contains the distal half of the transverse colon, descending colon, sigmoid colon, rectum, and superior anal canal.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Each subsection of the gut has an associated visceral afferent nerve that transmits sensory information from the viscera to the spinal cord.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] The visceral sensory information from the gut traveling to the spinal cord, termed the visceral afferent, is non-specific and overlaps with the somatic afferent nerves, which are very specific.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] A thorough patient history and physical examination is used to better understand the underlying cause of abdominal pain.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] After gathering a thorough history, one should perform a physical exam in order to identify important physical signs that might clarify the diagnosis, including a cardiovascular exam, lung exam, thorough abdominal exam, and for females, a genitourinary exam.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] If diagnosis remains unclear after history, examination, and basic investigations as above, then more advanced investigations may reveal a diagnosis.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] The management of abdominal pain depends on many factors, including the etiology of the pain.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Some behavioural changes implemented to prevent pain include: resting after a meal, chewing food completely and slowly, and avoiding stressful and high excitement situations after a meal.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Such at home strategies may reduce the need to seek professional assistance via prevention of future abdominal pain.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] In the emergency department, a person presenting with abdominal pain may initially require IV fluids due to decreased intake secondary to abdominal pain and possible emesis or vomiting.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Treatment for abdominal pain includes analgesia, such as non-opioid (ketorolac) and opioid medications (morphine, fentanyl).
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Choice of analgesia is dependent on the cause of the pain, as ketorolac can worsen some intra-abdominal processes.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Patients presenting to the emergency department with abdominal pain may receive a "GI cocktail" that includes an antacid (examples include omeprazole, famotidine, magnesium hydroxide, and calcium carbonate) and lidocaine.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] After addressing pain, there may be a role for antimicrobial treatment in some cases of abdominal pain.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Butylscopolamine (Buscopan) is used to treat cramping abdominal pain with some success.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Surgical management for causes of abdominal pain includes but is not limited to cholecystectomy, appendectomy, and exploratory laparotomy.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Below is a brief overview of abdominal pain emergencies.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] One well-known aspect of primary health care is its low prevalence of potentially dangerous abdominal pain causes.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Patients with abdominal pain have a higher percentage of unexplained complaints (category "no diagnosis") than patients with other symptoms (such as dyspnea or chest pain).
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Most people who suffer from stomach pain have a benign issue, like dyspepsia.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] In general, it is discovered that 20% to 25% of patients with abdominal pain have a serious condition that necessitates admission to an acute care hospital.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Abdominal pain is the reason about 3% of adults see their family physician.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Rates of emergency department (ED) visits in the United States for abdominal pain increased 18% from 2006 through to 2011.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] This was the largest increase out of 20 common conditions seen in the ED.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] The rate of ED use for nausea and vomiting also increased 18%.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] More time and resources are used on older patients with abdominal pain than on any other patient presentation in the emergency department (ED).
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Compared to younger patients with the same complaint, their length of stay is 20% longer, they need to be admitted almost half the time, and they need surgery 1/3 of the time.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Age does not reduce the total number of T cells, but it does reduce their functionality.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] The elderly person's ability to fight infection is weakened as a result.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Additionally, they have changed the strength and integrity of their skin and mucous membranes, which are physical barriers to infection.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] It is well known that older patients experience altered pain perception.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] The challenge of obtaining a sufficient history from an elderly patient can be attributed to multiple factors.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Reduced memory or hearing could make the issue worse.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] It is common to encounter stoicism combined with a fear of losing one's independence if a serious condition is discovered.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Changes in mental status, whether acute or chronic, are common.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Unique clinical challenges arise when pregnant women experience abdominal pain.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] First off, there are many possible causes of abdominal pain during pregnancy.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] These include intraabdominal diseases that arise incidentally during pregnancy as well as obstetric or gynecologic disorders associated with pregnancy.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Secondly, pregnancy modifies the natural history and clinical manifestation of numerous abdominal disorders.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Third, pregnancy modifies and limits the diagnostic assessment.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] For instance, concerns about fetal safety during pregnancy are raised by invasive exams and radiologic testing.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-pain] Fourth, while receiving therapy during pregnancy, the mother's and the fetus' interests need to be taken into account.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] Abdominal ultrasound examinations are performed by gastroenterologists or other specialists in internal medicine, radiologists, or sonographers trained for this procedure.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] Abdominal ultrasound can be used to diagnose abnormalities in various internal organs, such as the kidneys, liver, gallbladder, pancreas, spleen and abdominal aorta.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] If Doppler ultrasonography is added, the blood flow inside blood vessels can be evaluated as well (for example, to look for renal artery stenosis).
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] It is commonly used to examine the uterus and fetus during pregnancy; this is called obstetric ultrasonography.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] Abdominal ultrasound is commonly used in the setting of abdominal pain or an acute abdomen (sudden and/or severe abdominal pain syndrome in which surgical intervention might be necessary), in which it can diagnose appendicitis or cholecystitis.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] Ultrasound can also be used if there is suspicion of enlargement of one or more organs, such as used in screening for abdominal aortic aneurysm, investigation for splenomegaly or urinary retention.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] Ultrasound can be used for additional anatomical information for patients with an abnormal kidney function or pancreatic enzymes (pancreatic amylase and pancreatic lipase).
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] It can be used on the abdominal aorta to detect or exclude abdominal aortic aneurysm.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] For this purpose, the standard aortic measurement for abdominal aortic aneurysm is between the outer margins of the aortic wall.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] In cases of infectious mononucleosis, splenomegaly is a common symptom, and health care providers may consider using abdominal ultrasonography to get insight into a person's condition.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] However, because spleen size varies greatly, ultrasonography is not a valid technique for assessing spleen enlargement and should not be used in typical circumstances or to make routine decisions about fitness for playing sports.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] Ultrasound imaging is useful for detecting stones, for example kidney stones or gallstones, because they create a clearly visible ultrasound shadow behind the stone.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] Ultrasonography can be used to guide procedures such as treatment for kidney stones with extracorporeal shock wave lithotripsy, needle biopsies or paracentesis (needle drainage of free fluid inside the abdominal cavity).
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] In patients with deranged liver function tests, ultrasound may show increased liver size (hepatomegaly), increased reflectiveness (which might, for example, indicate cholestasis), gallbladder or bile duct diseases, or a tumor in the liver.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] Ultrasonography of liver tumors involves two stages: detection and characterization.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] Tumor detection is based on the performance of the method and should include morphometric information (three axes dimensions, volume) and topographic information (number, location specifying liver segment and lobe/lobes).
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] The specification of these data is important for staging liver tumors and prognosis.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] Tumor characterization is a complex process based on a sum of criteria leading towards tumor nature definition.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] Often, other diagnostic procedures, especially interventional ones, are no longer necessary.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] Ultrasonography of the kidneys is essential in the diagnosis and management of kidney-related diseases.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] The kidneys are easily examined, and most pathological changes in the kidneys are distinguishable with ultrasound.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] Disadvantages are troublesome imaging if a lot of gas is present inside the bowels, if there is a lot of abdominal fat, and that the quality of the imaging depends on the experience of the person performing it.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] The imaging occurs real-time and without sedation, so that the influence of movements can be assessed quickly.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] For example, by pressing the ultrasound probe against the gallbladder, a radiological Murphy's sign can be elicited.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] Through the abdominal wall, organs inside the pelvis can be seen, such as the urinary bladder or the ovaries and uterus in women.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] Because water is an excellent conductor for ultrasound waves, visualizing these structures often requires a well-filled urinary bladder (this means the patients has to drink plenty of water before the examination).
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] The liver can be imaged by swiping the probe sagittally from medial to lateral at the subcoastal region.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] However, if majority of the liver parenchyma is located high up in behind the ribs, the subject can be asked to breathe deeply to push down the liver into the abdomen for better visibility of liver.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] If the liver is still not visualised, then the subject can be rolled to the left lateral position to move the liver out of the ribs.
[src:appendicitis/abdominal-ultrasonography] Then, the ultrasound probe is rotated 90 degrees to access the liver in axial plane from the dome of the diaphragm until the lower segment of the liver.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] The campaign identifies over 500 tests and procedures and encourages doctors and patients to discuss, research, and possibly get second opinions, before proceeding with them.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] To conduct the campaign, the ABIM Foundation asks medical specialty societies to make five to ten recommendations for preventing overuse of a treatment in their field.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] The foundation then publicizes this information, and the medical specialty societies disseminate it to their members.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] The campaign has garnered both praise and criticism, and some of its ideas have spread to other countries.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] It does not include evaluation of its effects on costs, on discussions or on medical outcomes.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] Some doctors have said they lack time for the recommended discussions.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] In 2002 the ABIM Foundation published *Medical professionalism in the new millennium: a Physician Charter*.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] The charter states that physicians have a responsibility to promote health equity when some health resources are scarce.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] As a practical way of achieving distributive justice, in 2010 physician Howard Brody recommended that medical specialty societies, being stewards of a field, ought to publish a list of five things which they would like changed in their field and publicize it to their members.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] In 2011, the National Physicians Alliance tested a project in which it organized the creation of some "top 5 lists".
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] Analysis of the National Physician's Alliance project predicted that the health field could have saved US$6.8 billion in 2009 by cutting spending on the 15 services in the lists from three societies, out of total US health spending that year of US$2.5 trillion.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] US$5.8 billion of the savings were from one recommendation: using generic rather than brand name statin.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] Continuing this project, *Choosing Wisely* was created to organise the creation of more "lists of five," later ten, and their distribution to more physicians and patients.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] Executive boards of societies, with or without participation by members, identify practices which their field may overuse.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] Each recommendation in the program must have the support of clinical guidelines, evidence, or expert opinion.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] To participate in *Choosing Wisely*, each society developed list of tests, treatments, or services which that specialty commonly overuses.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] The society shares this information with their members, as well as organizations who can publicize to local community groups, and in each community patients and doctors can consider the information as they like.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] The ABIM Foundation gave grants to help societies participate.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] As of April 2018, there were 552 recommendations targeting a range of procedures to either question or avoid without special consideration.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] They can be searched online by key words, such as "back pain" but the numerous supporting footnotes on each recommendation are only in a pdf on the clinician page, without links to the papers.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] Between 2012 and 2023, more than 80 specialty societies highlighted examples.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] While these examples are no longer maintained and available on the website (www.choosingwisely.org), specialty societies are encouraged to publish individual lists.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] Many of these lists are accessible through https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/collections/choosing-wisely.html.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] In 2012 *The New York Times* said that the campaign was likely to "alter treatment standards in hospitals and doctors' offices nationwide" and one of their opinion writers said that many tests were unnecessary.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] CBS News said that "the evidence is on the initiative's side." *USA Today* noted that the campaign was "a rare coordinated effort among multiple medical societies".
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] While expressing the need for evidence-based healthcare recommendations, in 2012 *The Economist* found the *Choosing Wisely* recommendations to be weak because they are not enforceable.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] In an editorial published in the *Southwest Journal of Pulmonary and Critical Care*, Richard Robbin and Allen Thomas expressed concern that the campaign could be used by payers to limit options for doctors and patients.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] In February 2013 the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation provided USD $2.5 million in funding for the campaign, saying that the foundation wanted to "help increase the tangible impact of the *Choosing Wisely* campaign".
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] Based on what we have seen so far, we suspect that Choosing Wisely is much more about saving money than improving patient care.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] In 2015 a piece in *Newsweek* by Kurt Eichenwald described a controversy around the ABIM Foundation's lack of transparency about its finances and functioning.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] In 2016 campaign was described as an attempt to encourage doctors and patients to recognize the illusion of control or "therapeutic illusion" in choices to use treatments which have a basis outside of evidence-based medicine.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] In 2017 addiction specialists in Canada said the recommendation to wait for sobriety before treating depression was harmful and unjustified.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] A 2017 study reported that many patients and physicians found it challenging to use Choosing Wisely recommendations, particularly when the patient had symptoms, and the doctor recommended against a test.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] Barriers "included malpractice concern, patient requests for services, lack of time for shared decision making, and the number of tests recommended by specialists.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] Cedars–Sinai Medical Center in Los Angeles put 100 of the 552 Choosing Wisely items in its electronic medical records.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] These give warnings to doctors, but only after they have finished talking to patients and order a procedure or drug, so too late to have the recommended discussion.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] The *Choosing Wisely* campaign makes no provision to scientifically research its own efficacy, but academic centers are making plans to independently report on the impact of the campaign.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] The services targeted by the Choosing Wisely lists have broad variance in how much impact they can have on patients' care and costs.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] Doctors analyzed many services listed as low value by Choosing Wisely and other sources, and found that 25% or 42% of Medicare patients received at least one of these services in an average year, depending on definitions.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] The services represented 0.6% or 2.7% of Medicare costs and there was no significant pattern among types of physicians.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] The campaign has been cited as being part of a broader movement including many comparable campaigns.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] The German Network for Evidence Based Medicine considered adapting concepts from the program into the German healthcare system.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] In April 2014, Choosing Wisely Canada launched.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] Choosing Wisely Canada is organized by the Canadian Medical Association and the University of Toronto, and is chaired by Dr.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] English doctors "are worried how patients will perceive the initiative." In 2018, Norway launched *Gjør kloke valg* (lit.
[src:appendicitis/abim-foundation] 'Make smart choices') modeled on the Choosing Wisely program.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Appendicitis is primarily caused by a blockage of the hollow portion in the appendix.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] This blockage typically results from a faecolith, a calcified "stone" made of feces.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Some studies show a correlation between appendicoliths and disease severity.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Other factors such as inflamed lymphoid tissue from a viral infection, intestinal parasites, gallstone, or tumors may also lead to this blockage.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] When the appendix becomes blocked, it experiences increased pressure, reduced blood flow, and bacterial growth, resulting in inflammation.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] This combination of factors causes tissue injury and, ultimately, tissue death.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] If this process is left untreated, it can lead to the appendix rupturing, which releases bacteria into the abdominal cavity, potentially leading to severe complications.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The diagnosis of appendicitis is largely based on the person's signs and symptoms.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] In cases where the diagnosis is unclear, close observation, medical imaging, and laboratory tests can be helpful.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The two most commonly used imaging tests for diagnosing appendicitis are ultrasound and computed tomography (CT scan).
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] CT scan is more accurate than ultrasound in detecting acute appendicitis.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] However, ultrasound may be preferred as the first imaging test in children and pregnant women because of the risks associated with radiation exposure from CT scans.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Although ultrasound may aid in diagnosis, its main role is in identifying important differentials, such as ovarian pathology in females or mesenteric adenitis in children.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The standard treatment for acute appendicitis involves the surgical removal of the inflamed appendix.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] This procedure can be performed either through an open incision in the abdomen (laparotomy) or using minimally invasive techniques with small incisions and cameras (laparoscopy).
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Surgery is essential to reduce the risk of complications or potential death associated with the rupture of the appendix.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Antibiotics may be equally effective in certain cases of non-ruptured appendicitis, but 31% will undergo appendectomy within one year.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] It is one of the most common and significant causes of sudden abdominal pain.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] In 2015, approximately 11.6 million cases of appendicitis were reported, resulting in around 50,100 deaths worldwide.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] In the United States, appendicitis is one of the most common causes of sudden abdominal pain requiring surgery.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Annually, more than 300,000 individuals in the United States undergo surgical removal of their appendix.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The presentation of acute appendicitis includes acute abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, and fever.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] As the appendix becomes more swollen and inflamed, it begins to irritate the adjoining abdominal wall.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] This leads the pain to localize at the right lower quadrant.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] This classic migration of pain may not appear in children under three years.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] This pain can be triggered by a sharp pain feeling.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Pain from appendicitis may begin as dull pain around the navel.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] After several hours, the pain usually migrates towards the right lower quadrant, where it becomes localized.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Symptoms include localized findings in the right iliac fossa.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The abdominal wall becomes very sensitive to gentle pressure (palpation).
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] There is pain in the sudden release of deep tension in the lower abdomen (Blumberg's sign).
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] If the appendix is retrocecal (localized behind the cecum), even deep pressure in the right lower quadrant may fail to elicit tenderness (silent appendix).
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] This is because the cecum, distended with gas, protects the inflamed appendix from pressure.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Similarly, if the appendix lies entirely within the pelvis, there is typically a complete absence of abdominal rigidity.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] In such cases, a digital rectal examination elicits tenderness in the rectovesical pouch.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Coughing causes point tenderness in this area (McBurney's point), called Dunphy's sign.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Acute appendicitis seems to be the result of a primary obstruction of the appendix.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Once this obstruction occurs, the appendix becomes filled with mucus and swells.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] This continued production of mucus leads to increased pressures within the lumen and the walls of the appendix.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The increased pressure results in thrombosis and occlusion of the small vessels, and stasis of lymphatic flow.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] At this point, spontaneous recovery rarely occurs.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] As the occlusion of blood vessels progresses, the appendix becomes ischemic and then necrotic.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] As bacteria begin to leak out through the dying walls, pus forms within and around the appendix (suppuration).
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The result is appendiceal rupture (a 'burst appendix') causing peritonitis, which may lead to sepsis and in rare cases, death.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] These events are responsible for the slowly evolving abdominal pain and other commonly associated symptoms.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The causative agents include bezoars, foreign bodies, trauma, lymphadenitis and, most commonly, calcified fecal deposits that are known as appendicoliths or fecaliths.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The occurrence of obstructing fecaliths has attracted attention since their presence in people with appendicitis is higher in developed than in developing countries.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] In addition, an appendiceal fecalith is commonly associated with complicated appendicitis.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Fecal stasis and arrest may play a role, as demonstrated by people with acute appendicitis having fewer bowel movements per week compared with healthy controls.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The occurrence of a fecalith in the appendix was thought to be attributed to a right-sided fecal retention reservoir in the colon and a prolonged transit time.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] However, a prolonged transit time was not observed in subsequent studies.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Diverticular disease and adenomatous polyps were historically unknown and colon cancer was exceedingly rare in communities where appendicitis itself was rare or absent, such as various African communities.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Studies have implicated a transition to a Western diet lower in fiber in rising frequencies of appendicitis as well as the other aforementioned colonic diseases in these communities, and acute appendicitis has been shown to occur antecedent to cancer in the colon and rectum.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Several studies offer evidence that a low fiber intake is involved in the pathogenesis of appendicitis.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] This low intake of dietary fiber is in accordance with the occurrence of a right-sided fecal reservoir and the fact that dietary fiber reduces transit time.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The physician will ask questions to get the health history, assess the patient's symptoms, do a complete physical exam, and order both laboratory and imaging tests.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Appendicitis symptoms fall into two categories, typical and atypical.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Typical appendicitis is characterized by a migratory right iliac fossa pain associated with nausea, and anorexia, which can occur with or without vomiting and localized muscle stiffness/ generalized guarding.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] It is possible the pain could localize to the left lower quadrant in people with situs inversus totalis.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The combination of migrated umbilical pain to the right lower quadrant, loss of appetite for food, nausea, unsustained vomiting, and mild fever is classic.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Atypical histories lack this typical progression and may include pain in the right lower quadrant as an initial symptom.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Irritation of the peritoneum (inside lining of the abdominal wall) can lead to increased pain on movement, or jolting, for example going over speed bumps.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Atypical histories often require imaging with ultrasound or CT scanning.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] During the early stages of appendicitis diagnosis, it is common for physical exams to present inconspicuous findings.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Signs of inflammation become noticeable as the disease progresses.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] While there is no laboratory test specific for appendicitis, a complete blood count (CBC) is done to check for signs of infection or inflammation.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Although 70–90 percent of people with appendicitis may have an elevated white blood cell (WBC) count, many other abdominal and pelvic conditions can cause the WBC count to be elevated.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] However, a high WBC count may not alone represent a solid indicator of appendicitis but rather an inflammation but the neutrophil ratio was more sensitive and specific for acute appendicitis.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Several routine and non-routine laboratory tests have been investigated for discriminating simple and complicated appendicitis, but their diagnostic accuracy is uncertain.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] In children, neutrophil-lymphocyte ratio (NLR) demonstrates a high degree of accuracy in the diagnosis of acute appendicitis and distinguishes complicated appendicitis from simple appendicitis.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] 75–78 percent of the patients have neutrophilia.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Delta-neutrophil index (DNI) is a valuable parameter that helps in the diagnosis of histologically normal appendicitis and distinguishing between simple and complicated appendicitis.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] A C-reactive protein (CRP) blood test will be ordered by the doctor to find out if there are any further causes of inflammation.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The C-reactive protein/albumin (CRP/ALB) ratio can be a reliable predictor of complicated appendicitis.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The urinalysis is important for ruling out a urinary tract infection as the cause of abdominal pain.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The presence of more than 20 WBC per high-power field in the urine is more suggestive of a urinary tract disorder.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] If the patient is a female, a pregnancy test will be ordered.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] In children, the clinical examination is important to determine which children with abdominal pain should receive immediate surgical consultation and which should receive diagnostic imaging.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Because of the health risks of exposing children to radiation, ultrasound is the preferred first choice with CT scan being a legitimate follow-up if the ultrasound is inconclusive.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] CT scan is more accurate than ultrasound for the diagnosis of appendicitis in adults and adolescents.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] CT scan has a sensitivity of 94%, specificity of 95%.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Ultrasonography had an overall sensitivity of 86%, a specificity of 81%.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Abdominal ultrasonography, preferably with doppler sonography, is useful to detect appendicitis, especially in children.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Ultrasound can show the free fluid collection in the right iliac fossa, along with a visible appendix with increased blood flow when using color Doppler, and noncompressibility of the appendix, as it is essentially a walled-off abscess.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Other secondary sonographic signs of acute appendicitis include the presence of echogenic mesenteric fat surrounding the appendix and the acoustic shadowing of an appendicolith.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] In some cases (approximately 5%), ultrasonography of the iliac fossa does not reveal any abnormalities despite the presence of appendicitis.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] This false-negative finding is especially true of early appendicitis before the appendix has become significantly distended.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Also, false-negative findings are more common in adults where larger amounts of fat and bowel gas make visualizing the appendix technically difficult.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Despite these limitations, sonographic imaging with experienced hands can often distinguish between appendicitis and other diseases with similar symptoms.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Some of these conditions include inflammation of lymph nodes near the appendix or pain originating from other pelvic organs such as the ovaries or Fallopian tubes.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Ultrasounds may be either done by the radiology department or by the emergency physician.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Where it is readily available, computed tomography (CT) has become frequently used, especially in people whose diagnosis is not obvious on history and physical examination.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Although some concerns about interpretation are identified, a 2019 Cochrane review found that the sensitivity and specificity of CT for the diagnosis of acute appendicitis in adults was high.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Concerns about radiation tend to limit use of CT in pregnant women and in children, especially with the increasingly widespread usage of MRI.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The accurate diagnosis of appendicitis is multi-tiered, with the size of the appendix having the strongest positive predictive value, while indirect features can either increase or decrease sensitivity and specificity.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] A size of over 6 mm is both 95% sensitive and specific for appendicitis.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] However, because the appendix can be filled with fecal material, causing intraluminal distention, this criterion has shown limited utility in more recent meta-analyses.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] This is as opposed to ultrasound, in which the wall of the appendix can be more easily distinguished from intraluminal feces.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] In such scenarios, ancillary features such as increased wall enhancement as compared to adjacent bowel and inflammation of the surrounding fat, or fat stranding, can be supportive of the diagnosis.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] However, their absence does not preclude it.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] In severe cases with perforation, an adjacent phlegmon or abscess can be seen.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Dense fluid layering in the pelvis can also result, related to either pus or enteric spillage.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] When patients are thin or younger, the relative absence of fat can make the appendix and surrounding fat stranding difficult to see.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) use has become increasingly common for diagnosis of appendicitis in children and pregnant patients due to the radiation dosage that, while of nearly negligible risk in healthy adults, can be harmful to children or the developing baby.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] In pregnancy, it is more useful during the second and third trimester, particularly as the enlargening uterus displaces the appendix, making it difficult to find by ultrasound.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The periappendiceal stranding that is reflected on CT by fat stranding on MRI appears as an increased fluid signal on T2 weighted sequences.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] First-trimester pregnancies are usually not candidates for MRI, as the fetus is still undergoing organogenesis, and there are no long-term studies to date regarding its potential risks or side effects.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] In general, plain abdominal radiography (PAR) is not useful in making the diagnosis of appendicitis and should not be routinely obtained from a person being evaluated for appendicitis.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Plain abdominal films may be useful for the detection of ureteral calculi, small bowel obstruction, or perforated ulcer, but these conditions are rarely confused with appendicitis.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] An opaque fecalith can be identified in the right lower quadrant in fewer than 5% of people being evaluated for appendicitis.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] A barium enema has proven to be a poor diagnostic tool for appendicitis.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] While failure of the appendix to fill during a barium enema has been associated with appendicitis, up to 20% of normal appendices do not fill.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Several scoring systems have been developed to try to identify people who are likely to have appendicitis.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The performance of scores such as the Alvarado score and the Pediatric Appendicitis Score, however, are variable.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The Alvarado score is the most known scoring system.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] A score below 5 suggests against a diagnosis of appendicitis, whereas a score of 7 or more is predictive of acute appendicitis.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] In a person with an equivocal score of 5 or 6, a CT scan or ultrasound exam may be used to reduce the rate of negative appendectomy.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Even for clinically certain appendicitis, routine histopathology examination of appendectomy specimens is of value for identifying unsuspected pathologies requiring further postoperative management.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] No sign of appendicitis in specimens, negative appendectomy, varies but has been estimated to occur in 13% of specimens.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Notably, appendix cancer is found incidentally in about 1% of appendectomy specimens.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Pathology diagnosis of appendicitis can be made by detecting a neutrophilic infiltrate of the muscularis propria.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Periappendicitis (inflammation of tissues around the appendix) is often found in conjunction with other abdominal pathology.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Women: A pregnancy test is important for all women of childbearing age since an ectopic pregnancy can have signs and symptoms similar to those of appendicitis.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Other obstetrical/ gynecological causes of similar abdominal pain in women include pelvic inflammatory disease, ovarian torsion, menarche, dysmenorrhea, endometriosis, and Mittelschmerz (the passing of an egg in the ovaries approximately two weeks before menstruation).
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Adults: new-onset Crohn's disease, ulcerative colitis, regional enteritis, cholecystitis, renal colic, perforated peptic ulcer, pancreatitis, rectus sheath hematoma, appendiceal mucinous lesions and epiploic appendagitis.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Elderly: diverticulitis, intestinal obstruction, colonic carcinoma, mesenteric ischemia, leaking aortic aneurysm.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The term "pseudoappendicitis" is used to describe a condition mimicking appendicitis.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] It can be associated with *Yersinia enterocolitica*.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Acute appendicitis is typically managed by surgery.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Antibiotics are safe and effective for treating uncomplicated appendicitis and may be associated with a lower rate of overall complications, but in some patients the appendicits does recur.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] While 51% of patients who were treated with antibiotics did not need an appendectomy three years after treatment, a different study found that 44% of patients eventually received an appendectomy within 10 years.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Antibiotics are less effective if an appendicolith is present.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The cost effectiveness of surgery versus antibiotics is unclear.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Using antibiotics to prevent potential postoperative complications in emergency appendectomy procedures is recommended, and the antibiotics are effective when given to a person before, during, or after surgery.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Pain medications (such as morphine) do not appear to affect the accuracy of the clinical diagnosis of appendicitis and therefore should be given early in the patient's care.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Historically there were concerns among some general surgeons that analgesics would affect the clinical exam in children, and some recommended that they not be given until the surgeon was able to examine the person.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The surgical procedure for the removal of the appendix is called an appendectomy.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] A negative appendectomy constitutes the removal of a normal appendix with no sign of inflammation in histopathology examination.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The prevalence of negative appendectomy varies but has been estimated to 13%.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Appendectomy can be performed through open or laparoscopic surgery.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Laparoscopic appendectomy has several advantages over open appendectomy as an intervention for acute appendicitis.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] For over a century, laparotomy (open appendectomy) was the standard treatment for acute appendicitis.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] This procedure consists of the removal of the infected appendix through a single large incision in the lower right area of the abdomen.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The incision in a laparotomy is usually 2 to 3 inches (51 to 76 mm) long.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] During an open appendectomy, the person with suspected appendicitis is placed under general anesthesia to keep the muscles completely relaxed and to keep the person unconscious.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The incision is two to three inches (76 mm) long, and it is made in the right lower abdomen, several inches above the hip bone.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Once the incision opens the abdomen cavity, and the appendix is identified, the surgeon removes the infected tissue and cuts the appendix from the surrounding tissue.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] After careful and close inspection of the infected area, and ensuring there are no signs that surrounding tissues are damaged or infected.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] In case of complicated appendicitis managed by an emergency open appendectomy, abdominal drainage (a temporary tube from the abdomen to the outside to avoid abscess formation) may be inserted, but this may increase the hospital stay.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The surgeon will start closing the incision.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] This means sewing the muscles and using surgical staples or stitches to close the skin up.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] To prevent infections, the incision is covered with a sterile bandage or surgical adhesive.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Laparoscopic appendectomy was introduced in 1983 and has become an increasingly prevalent intervention for acute appendicitis.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] This surgical procedure consists of making three to four incisions in the abdomen, each 0.25 to 0.5 inches (6.4 to 12.7 mm) long.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] This type of appendectomy is made by inserting a special surgical tool called a laparoscope into one of the incisions.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The laparoscope is connected to a monitor outside the person's body, and it is designed to help the surgeon inspect the infected area in the abdomen.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The other two incisions are made for the specific removal of the appendix by using surgical instruments.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Laparoscopic surgery requires general anesthesia, and it can last up to two hours.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Laparoscopic appendectomy has several advantages over open appendectomy, including a shorter post-operative recovery, less post-operative pain, and a lower superficial surgical site infection rate.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] However, the occurrence of an intra-abdominal abscess is almost three times more prevalent in laparoscopic appendectomy than open appendectomy.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] In pediatric patients, the high mobility of the cecum allows externalization of the appendix through the umbilicus, and the entire procedure can be performed with a single incision.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Laparoscopic-assisted transumbilical appendectomy is a relatively recent technique but with a long published series and very good surgical and aesthetic results.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The treatment begins by keeping the person who will be having surgery from eating or drinking for a given period, usually overnight.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] An intravenous drip is used to hydrate the person who will be having surgery.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Antibiotics given intravenously such as cefuroxime and metronidazole may be administered early to help kill bacteria and thus reduce the spread of infection in the abdomen and postoperative complications in the abdomen or wound.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Equivocal cases may become more difficult to assess with antibiotic treatment and benefit from serial examinations.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] If the stomach is empty (no food in the past six hours), general anaesthesia is usually used.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Otherwise, spinal anaesthesia may be used.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Once the decision to perform an appendectomy has been made, the preparation procedure takes approximately one to two hours.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Meanwhile, the surgeon will explain the surgery procedure and will present the risks that must be considered when performing an appendectomy.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The risks differ depending on the state of the appendix: if the appendix has not ruptured, the complication rate is only about 3%, but if the appendix has ruptured, the complication rate rises to almost 59%.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The most usual complications that can occur are pneumonia, hernia of the incision, thrombophlebitis, bleeding and adhesions.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Evidence indicates that a delay in obtaining surgery after admission results in no measurable difference in outcomes to the person with appendicitis.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Most patients undergo emergency surgery, but delayed surgery (interval appendectomy) has been investigated for certain patients.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Delaying surgery for weeks may increase the risk of intra-abdominal abscess in patients suffering from appendicitis and presenting with an appendiceal mass (e.g., phlegmon or abscess).
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The harms and benefits of delaying surgery for other complications are uncertain.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The surgeon will explain how long the recovery process should take.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Abdomen hair is usually removed to avoid complications that may appear regarding the incision.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] In most cases, patients going in for surgery experience nausea or vomiting that require medication before surgery.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Antibiotics, along with pain medication, may be administered before appendectomies.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Hospital lengths of stay typically range from a few hours to a few days but can be a few weeks if complications occur.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The recovery process may vary depending on the severity of the condition: if the appendix had ruptured or not before surgery.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Appendix surgery recovery is generally much faster if the appendix does not rupture.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] It is important that people undergoing surgery respect their doctor's advice and limit their physical activity so the tissues can heal.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Recovery after an appendectomy may not require diet changes or a lifestyle change.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The length of hospital stays for appendicitis varies on the severity of the condition.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] A study from the United States found that in 2010, the average appendicitis hospital stay was 1.8 days.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] For stays where the person's appendix had ruptured, the average length of stay was 5.2 days.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] After surgery, the patient will be transferred to a postanesthesia care unit, so their vital signs can be closely monitored to detect anesthesia- or surgery-related complications.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Pain medication may be administered if necessary.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] After patients are completely awake, they are moved to a hospital room to recover.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Most individuals will be offered clear liquids the day after the surgery, then progress to a regular diet when the intestines start to function correctly.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Patients are recommended to sit on the edge of the bed and walk short distances several times a day.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Moving is mandatory, and pain medication may be given if necessary.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Full recovery from appendectomies takes about four to six weeks but can be prolonged to up to eight weeks if the appendix has ruptured.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Most people with appendicitis recover quickly after surgical treatment, but complications can occur if treatment is delayed or if peritonitis occurs.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Recovery time depends on age, condition, complications, and other circumstances, including the amount of alcohol consumption, but usually is between 10 and 28 days.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] For young children (around ten years old), the recovery takes three weeks.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The possibility of peritonitis is the reason why acute appendicitis warrants rapid evaluation and treatment.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] People with suspected appendicitis may have to undergo a medical evacuation.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Appendectomies have occasionally been performed in emergency conditions (i.e., not in a proper hospital) when a timely medical evacuation was impossible.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Typical acute appendicitis responds quickly to appendectomy and occasionally will resolve spontaneously.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] If appendicitis resolves spontaneously, it remains controversial whether an elective interval appendectomy should be performed to prevent a recurrent episode of appendicitis.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Atypical appendicitis (associated with suppurative appendicitis) is more challenging to diagnose and is more apt to be complicated even when operated early.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] In either condition, prompt diagnosis and appendectomy yield the best results with full recovery in two to four weeks usually.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Mortality and severe complications are unusual but do occur, especially if peritonitis persists and is untreated.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Another entity known as the appendicular lump is talked about.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] It happens when the appendix is not removed early during infection, and the omentum and intestine adhere to it, forming a palpable lump.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] During this period, surgery is risky unless there is pus formation evident by fever and toxicity or by ultrasound.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Medical management treats the condition.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] An unusual complication of an appendectomy is "stump appendicitis": inflammation occurs in the remnant appendiceal stump left after a prior incomplete appendectomy.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Stump appendicitis can occur months to years after initial appendectomy and can be identified with imaging modalities such as ultrasound.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The history of appendicitis traces back to ancient medical texts, though its clear clinical understanding emerged in the 19th century.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Berengario da Carpi provided the first recorded description of the appendix in the 16th century, followed by Andreas Vesalius and Gabriele Falloppio.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Clinical understanding progressed in the 18th and 19th centuries, marked by Lorenz Heister's autopsy findings, Claudius Aymand's surgical intervention, and J.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Prior to the use of the term *appendicitis*, it was described with terms including *perityphlitis*, *side sickness*, *typhlitis*, *paratyphlitis*, *iliac passion*, and *extra-peritoneal abscess of the right iliac fossa*.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] The term "appendicitis" was coined by the American physician Reginald Heber Fitz in 1886, leading to standardized diagnosis and treatment, including Charles McBurney's identification of McBurney's point.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Modern appendectomy techniques evolved in the early 20th century, coinciding with advancements in pathology, notably demonstrated by Ludwig Aschoff in 1908.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Public awareness of appendicitis, and the fact that it can be successfully treated surgically, was significantly increased in 1902 when Sir Frederick Treves, 1st Baronet treated appendicitis in Edward VII two days before his coronation.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Appendicitis is most common between the ages of 5 and 40.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] In the United States, there were nearly 293,000 hospitalizations involving appendicitis in 2010.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Appendicitis is one of the most frequent diagnoses for emergency department visits resulting in hospitalization among children ages 5–17 years in the United States.
[src:appendicitis/appendicitis] Adults presenting to the emergency department with a known family history of appendicitis are more likely to have this disease than those without.
